    {
      "id": "c04d5285_611bde5e",
      "file_path": "cps-ncmp-service/src/main/java/org/onap/cps/ncmp/impl/datajobs/subscription/cmavc/CmAvcEventSingleConsumer.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 45,
      "message": "if you remove the single consumer and keep only the batch consumer with max-poll-records set to 1, wouldn't we again hit the issue with the forwarding performance drop? So in that way still a transaction would be created for each event. Also if you set the max-poll-records to 1 what would happen if the currently running instance have more then 1 thread that reads the topic? In that way I assume only 1 thread would get the event batch that contains only 1 event and the other thread(s) would be idle for some time which may slow down processing further. What do you think about this?",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 8559,
        "name": "Daniel Molnar",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "dani.molnar2001@gmail.com",
        "username": "molnardani"
      },
      "updated": "2026-03-17 09:50:54.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "920b257d_9fed7c74",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "1ad510f4_4bc7b922",
      "file_path": "cps-ncmp-service/src/main/java/org/onap/cps/ncmp/impl/datajobs/subscription/cmavc/CmAvcEventBatchConsumer.java",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 47,
      "message": "shouldn't we also check for the value of ncmp.kafka.eos.enabled property? Because to make this code work both ncmp.kafka.eos.enabled and ncmp.notifications.avc-event-consumer.batch-enabled should be set to true",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 8559,
        "name": "Daniel Molnar",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "dani.molnar2001@gmail.com",
        "username": "molnardani"
      },
      "updated": "2026-03-17 11:26:19.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "2e16092e_7998e96a",
      "file_path": "cps-ncmp-service/src/test/groovy/org/onap/cps/ncmp/impl/datajobs/subscription/cmavc/CmAvcEventBatchConsumerSpec.groovy",
      "patchset_number": 1,
      "line": 43,
      "message": "I am not very familiar with tests written in groovy, so I am not sure if it is possible to implement such test in this way what I am about to describe, but I know that we definitely have similar tests to validate that any exception in the batch sending will be handled correctly and eventually it will be sent out correctly. I believe it would be a valid end-to-end test to assert the following scenario:\n\n- Event batch of 500 arrivives to the input topic\n- sending the 251st event would throw an exception so the whole batch is rolled back\n- For second try, the batch propagation passes, and assert that on the final topic there are exactly 500 events and no more\n\nNext to spring boot test we also use EmbeddedKafka which starts an in memory kafka instance so we can validate the functionality better than using mocks\n\nWhat do you think about this?",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 8559,
        "name": "Daniel Molnar",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "dani.molnar2001@gmail.com",
        "username": "molnardani"
      },
      "updated": "2026-03-19 09:18:56.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
